AVIAN INFLUENZA - EASTERN ASIA (113): MALAYSIA
**********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: 14 Sep 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Office International des Epizooties(OIE), Disease
Information, Vol. 17 - No. 37
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/a_current.htm#Sec2>
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/a_current.htm#Sec3>

[1]
Highly Pathogenic Avian Influenza in Malaysia (peninsular)
Follow-up report No. 1
See also: 10 Sep 2004, 20 Aug 2004
Information received on 6 Sep 2004 from Dr Hawari Bin Hussein,
Director General, Department of Veterinary Service, Ministry of
Agriculture, Kuala Lumpur:
End of previous report period: 19 Aug 2004 (see Disease Information,
17 [34], 238, dated 20 Aug 2004).
End of this report period: 27 Aug 2004.
Diagnosis:
A. Laboratories where diagnosis was made:
- Veterinary Research Institute (Ipoh, Perak),
- Faculty of Veterinary Medicine, University Putra Malaysia (Serdang,
Selangor).
B. Diagnostic tests used:
- RT-PCR(1),
- haemagglutinin gene sequencing.
C. Causal agent: avian influenza virus subtype H5N1, 97 percent
homologous to the avian influenza virus H5N1 isolated in 2004 in
Thailand (isolate LFPM) and Vietnam (isolate C57).
Epidemiology:
A. Source of agent / origin of infection: very likely from a
neighbouring country.
B. Mode of spread: under investigation.
C. Other epidemiological details: to date, tests on samples collected
within a 1-km radius of the infected flock have failed to detect any
evidence of avian influenza virus infection.
Control measures during reporting period:
- depopulation of poultry and other birds within a 1-km radius of the
infected flock was completed on 20 Aug 2004;
- quarantine within a 10-km radius of the infected flock was maintained;
- clinical surveillance within a 10-km radius of the infected flock
was maintained;
- sample collection for virological surveillance with a 10-km radius
of the infected flock;
- restrictions on the movement of birds and their products to other
states were maintained;
- clinical surveillance in the whole of Peninsular Malaysia.
(1) RT-PCR: reverse transcriptase - polymerase chain reaction
******
[2]
Highly Pathogenic Avian Influenza In Malaysia (peninsular)
Follow-up report No. 2
See also: 10 Sep 2004, 20 Aug 2004
Information received on 9 Sep 2004 from Dr Hawari Bin Hussein,
Director General, Department of Veterinary Service, Ministry of
Agriculture, Kuala Lumpur:
End of previous report period: 27 Aug 2004 (see Disease Information,
17 [37], 255, dated 10 Sep 2004).
End of this report period: 9 Sep 2004.
New outbreak:
Location Kelantan State, Tumpat district, Belian village
No. of outbreaks: 1
The new outbreak area is 5 km from the previous infected flock (in
Pasir Pekan village).
Description of affected population in the new outbreak: a flock
consisting of 50 quails and 20 village chickens. The quails were
adult layers and reared in a raised floor cage. The village chickens
were of mixed ages and reared free-range.
Total number of animals in the new outbreak:
species: avi
susceptible: 2035*
cases: 30**
deaths: 30**
destroyed: 2005
slaughtered: 0
* Susceptible population within a 1-km radius of the infected flock.
Details are as follows: 1608 village chickens, 93 ducks, 68 bantam
chickens, 60 quails, 9 geese, 4 turkeys and 193 other birds.
** 20 quails and 10 village chickens.
Control measures during reporting period:
- depopulation of poultry and other birds within a 1-km radius of the
infected flock was completed on 9 Sep 2004;
- quarantine within a 10-km radius of the infected flock;
- clinical surveillance within a 10-km radius of the infected flock;
- sample collection for virological surveillance with a 10-km radius
of the infected flock;
- restrictions on the movement of birds and their products to other
states were maintained;
- clinical surveillance was maintained in the whole of Peninsular Malaysia.
